00:01:25.339 --> 00:01:28.980
So RStudio Workbench is at its core

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:31.820
an R-centric development environment.

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:34.139
If you've used the RStudio open source software,

00:01:34.139 --> 00:01:38.139
either at the desktop level or through RStudio server,

00:01:38.139 --> 00:01:39.820
you're likely familiar with this experience.

00:01:39.820 --> 00:01:41.339
You have a development environment

00:01:41.339 --> 00:01:43.059
that gives you lots of tooling around working

00:01:43.059 --> 00:01:43.900
with R.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:46.620
Ways to manage packages, ways to manage your environment,

00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:48.860
edit files, write code, debug.

00:01:48.860 --> 00:01:49.980
All these tools are part

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:53.139
of the RStudio development environment.

00:01:53.139 --> 00:01:55.379
RStudio Workbench gives you this environment accessible

00:01:55.379 --> 00:01:56.419
through a browser.

00:01:56.419 --> 00:01:59.099
It's typically something that organizations will install,

00:01:59.099 --> 00:02:01.660
host and manage within their own infrastructure,

00:02:01.660 --> 00:02:03.500
within their own firewalls.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:05.419
We'll talk about how that model's a little bit different

00:02:05.419 --> 00:02:06.739
with SageMaker throughout the course

00:02:06.739 --> 00:02:08.300
of our presentation today.

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:11.300
One of the things that RStudio Workbench provides

00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:13.259
that you don't find in the open source version

00:02:13.259 --> 00:02:15.699
is you have the opportunity to support multiple versions

00:02:15.699 --> 00:02:17.179
of R concurrently.

00:02:17.179 --> 00:02:18.779
And there's some additional functionality

00:02:18.779 --> 00:02:20.899
that's also available related to security

00:02:20.899 --> 00:02:25.179
and scalability in RStudio Workbench itself.

00:02:25.179 --> 00:02:26.820
Another kind of important component

00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:28.460
of the RStudio development environment,

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:31.020
especially as it relates to the topic today,

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:33.699
is that there are tools there for Python interoperability.

00:02:33.699 --> 00:02:36.580
So the ability to work in R and Python kind

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:38.820
of simultaneously is something that's available.

00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:40.860
And that's not restrictive just to RStudio Workbench.

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:43.179
That's just a feature of really the R language,

00:02:43.179 --> 00:02:45.139
but there's some tooling inside of RStudio,

00:02:45.139 --> 00:02:46.460
the development environment,

00:02:46.460 --> 00:02:47.699
that make it a little bit easier to work

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:52.619
with Python frameworks within kind of within an R context.

00:02:52.619 --> 00:02:54.940
And we'll talk to why that's important here in a moment.

00:02:57.820 --> 00:02:59.500
Amazon SageMaker, on the other hand,

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:02.380
is a fully managed machine learning service.

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:07.179
There are a large and growing number of services available

00:03:07.179 --> 00:03:08.259
through SageMaker.

00:03:08.259 --> 00:03:11.259
In fact, at AWS reInvent just last week,

00:03:11.259 --> 00:03:12.460
they announced some new functionality

00:03:12.460 --> 00:03:14.020
and some new features that are being made available

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:14.860
on the platform.

00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:17.119
So it's continuing to grow, continuing to evolve.

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:19.839
It's one of the fastest growing kind of AWS products

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:21.639
that Amazon offers.

00:03:21.639 --> 00:03:23.600
And for good reason, it's highly scalable.

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:24.679
It provides access to a lot

00:03:24.679 --> 00:03:26.800
of native machine learning algorithms.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:28.720
You have an integrated machine learning environment

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:30.880
for doing development and testing and model deployment

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:31.919
and things like that.

00:03:31.919 --> 00:03:34.199
And then it gives you a really nice production ready way

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:37.080
to deploy machine learning models, track those models,

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:40.160
monitor them, kind of everything within the scope

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:43.440
of model development and machine learning operations

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.520
is available through the SageMaker platform.

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:49.839
With this said, it might be kind of easy to look

00:03:49.839 --> 00:03:52.119
at these two different products

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:53.479
and these two different platforms

00:03:53.479 --> 00:03:56.080
and to kind of pit them against one another, right?

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:59.320
SageMaker provides a machine learning

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:00.520
kind of development environment

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:02.080
that's built on top of JupyterLab.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:04.600
They provide lots of really nice functionality.

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:05.679
And RStudio, on the other hand,

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:08.000
provides a development environment heavily focused

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:09.600
on the R user.

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:13.080
Thankfully, instead of putting these two things

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:15.199
against one another, instead what's happened is

00:04:15.199 --> 00:04:16.640
we've combined the two, right?

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:19.920
We've said, look, what if we have RStudio

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:22.959
as an available editor, as an available tool

00:04:22.959 --> 00:04:23.799
through the...

00:04:28.799 --> 00:04:30.679
And that's been driven in large part by...

00:04:30.679 --> 00:04:32.679
I'm just gonna mute someone real quick.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:36.119
And this effort has largely been driven

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:37.839
by the R community.

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:41.040
As our customer base has grown, both professionally

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:42.760
as well as just the open source users

00:04:42.760 --> 00:04:45.320
who use RStudio products every day,

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:46.880
there's been a growing interest

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:49.040
in having some sort of solution offered

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:51.320
through the SageMaker platform.

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:52.480
And for good reason, right?

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:54.559
SageMaker provides all these functionalities

00:04:54.559 --> 00:04:56.200
around machine learning and tooling

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:59.079
that R users are likely very attracted to.

00:04:59.079 --> 00:05:00.959
But the RStudio IDE is the place

00:05:00.959 --> 00:05:03.160
where R users feel most at home.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:05.239
And so we've worked closely with the SageMaker team

00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:07.079
and we're happy to announce that RStudio

00:05:07.079 --> 00:05:08.760
is an editor and an environment

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:12.440
that is now natively available through Amazon SageMaker.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:14.160
And we'll take a look at what that looks like

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:15.000
in just a moment.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:17.399
And we're really excited about this, right?

00:05:17.399 --> 00:05:19.519
We think this is an awesome opportunity,

00:05:19.519 --> 00:05:23.040
not only for us, but for R users kind of everywhere

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:25.200
within organizations throughout the globe

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:27.200
to use a tool in an environment

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:28.920
that they're comfortable and familiar with

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:32.839
with the enhancements provided by the SageMaker platform.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:36.799
So a little bit of a summary of what this is, right?

00:05:36.799 --> 00:05:38.359
It's a managed RStudio solution,

00:05:38.359 --> 00:05:41.679
which means that running RStudio Workbench on SageMaker

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:44.640
means that as an organization or as an individual,

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:47.200
you do not need to set up, install,

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:48.920
maintain RStudio yourself.

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:50.760
Instead, that's handled on the SageMaker side.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.320
It's simply something that you choose to opt into

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:55.600
when you set up your SageMaker domain.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:00.279
It uses, if you have an existing RStudio Workbench license,

00:06:00.279 --> 00:06:01.600
you can use that license

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:04.679
and you can carry that over into SageMaker.

00:06:04.679 --> 00:06:08.100
It gives you access to scalable Amazon resources,

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:11.440
easy access to additional SageMaker features

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:14.320
and capabilities like some of the machine learning abilities

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:16.160
and model deployment and management

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.359
and other things that are part of

00:06:18.359 --> 00:06:20.679
what SageMaker offers to users.

00:06:20.679 --> 00:06:22.880
And you have flexible compute resources

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:23.760
for the different workloads

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.000
that you might be involved in and engaged in.

