is the RStudio editor,

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:03.280
the RStudio development environment.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:06.000
The other option that we have here is Cluster.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.039
Again, the only option available to us is SageMaker.

00:11:09.039 --> 00:11:11.280
And this is just kind of an interesting note,

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:12.280
a little bit of a side note,

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:13.440
but I think it's worth noting.

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:15.559
And that is the fact that Amazon

00:11:15.559 --> 00:11:19.039
is one of the first groups that's taken the launcher,

00:11:19.039 --> 00:11:21.400
which is a component of RStudio Workbench

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:22.960
that allows it to integrate

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:26.679
with other execution engines like Kubernetes.

00:11:26.679 --> 00:11:28.539
But Amazon's one of the first groups that's taken that

00:11:28.539 --> 00:11:30.580
and created a custom backend for it.

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:33.460
And that custom backend is this SageMaker backend.

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:36.539
That's only available through the SageMaker integration.

00:11:36.539 --> 00:11:38.940
But once I've selected SageMaker as my cluster,

00:11:38.940 --> 00:11:42.340
I can then define, we'll first talk about this image.

00:11:42.340 --> 00:11:43.679
I can define the Docker image.

00:11:43.679 --> 00:11:47.179
I want this particular session to be run on.

00:11:47.179 --> 00:11:48.219
As it stands currently,

00:11:48.219 --> 00:11:50.719
there's only one default image available,

00:11:50.719 --> 00:11:53.739
but that's something that will change in the near future.

00:11:53.739 --> 00:11:55.359
And then the instance type here

00:11:55.359 --> 00:11:57.760
is where I will select the EC2 instance

00:11:57.760 --> 00:11:59.520
or the Amazon compute instance

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:02.080
that I want this particular session to run on.

00:12:02.080 --> 00:12:03.559
And there's a whole host of options.

00:12:03.559 --> 00:12:05.719
And this is one of the great kind of benefits

00:12:05.719 --> 00:12:07.320
of this architecture.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:10.000
Because one, I don't have to,

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:11.119
again, like I mentioned previously,

00:12:11.119 --> 00:12:12.460
as an organization,

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:14.760
I don't have to manage and maintain this, right?

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:15.880
This is something that's set up

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:17.599
as part of my SageMaker domain.

00:12:17.599 --> 00:12:19.299
SageMaker is the owner,

00:12:19.299 --> 00:12:22.479
the maintainer of the RStudio Workbench environment.

00:12:22.479 --> 00:12:24.039
But automatically out of the box,

00:12:24.039 --> 00:12:25.539
if I go this route,

00:12:25.539 --> 00:12:28.460
I have a very flexible kind of compute engine

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:29.460
that I can lean on.

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:31.539
Because I can decide when I start a new session,

00:12:31.539 --> 00:12:33.219
what type of resources I might need.

00:12:33.219 --> 00:12:34.979
Do I need heavy compute?

00:12:34.979 --> 00:12:37.539
Do I have a very memory intensive process?

00:12:37.539 --> 00:12:39.320
Am I gonna be doing some really heavy model training

00:12:39.320 --> 00:12:40.380
with very big data?

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:42.900
And I can make an intelligent selection at this point

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:45.299
about what type of EC2 instance

00:12:45.299 --> 00:12:48.859
I want this particular session to run on

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:51.820
so that I have the appropriate resources available to me

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:53.039
as I run this session.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:55.599
The other thing that's worth noting here

00:12:55.599 --> 00:12:56.960
is that as multiple users

00:12:56.960 --> 00:12:59.960
are engaged with RStudio through SageMaker,

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:01.719
they're working kind of independently

00:13:01.719 --> 00:13:03.039
in their own environments.

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:05.880
So that if one user does something in their environment,

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:07.200
for example, reads data in

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:08.859
that consumes all available memory

00:13:08.859 --> 00:13:11.619
or consumes all available CPU,

00:13:11.619 --> 00:13:14.359
they don't impact or negatively impact the other users

00:13:14.359 --> 00:13:17.559
because they're all kind of in their independent environments.

