we can then grab what the best training job was

00:33:57.760 --> 00:34:02.560
out of the status of the tuning job that we've run.

00:34:02.560 --> 00:34:04.800
We can investigate what the metrics are of that model,

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:07.359
and we can also figure out where that model's being stored

00:34:07.359 --> 00:34:08.280
inside of S3.

00:34:08.280 --> 00:34:09.639
So we have lots of functionality

00:34:09.639 --> 00:34:10.959
around how we manipulate the models

00:34:10.959 --> 00:34:12.879
that get created from our tuning jobs.

00:34:12.879 --> 00:34:14.879
And then at this point, we have two different options.

00:34:14.879 --> 00:34:16.260
Typically the point of building a model

00:34:16.260 --> 00:34:18.479
isn't just to build the model itself,

00:34:18.479 --> 00:34:20.320
but to then do something with it,

00:34:20.320 --> 00:34:21.679
to leverage that model in some way,

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:23.159
to run new data through the model

00:34:23.679 --> 00:34:25.120
and generate predictions on that new data.

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:27.959
And SageMaker provides kind of two frameworks for doing that.

00:34:27.959 --> 00:34:30.399
One is batch transformations,

00:34:30.399 --> 00:34:32.280
which is, I'm not necessarily looking

00:34:32.280 --> 00:34:34.959
for real-time inference,

00:34:34.959 --> 00:34:38.520
but rather I'm looking for a way to run a batch of new data

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:41.239
through my model all at one time.

00:34:41.239 --> 00:34:43.040
And that's something that's supported

00:34:43.040 --> 00:34:44.760
through the SageMaker SDK.

00:34:44.760 --> 00:34:47.719
This walks through an example of setting up,

00:34:47.719 --> 00:34:49.179
and I'm not gonna walk through it right now,

00:34:49.179 --> 00:34:50.040
but this walks through an example

00:34:50.040 --> 00:34:52.199
of how to set up that batch transformation

00:34:52.199 --> 00:34:55.639
and run a set of new test data through the model,

00:34:55.639 --> 00:34:56.719
collect those results,

00:34:56.719 --> 00:34:58.959
and then compare them to the original observations.

00:34:58.959 --> 00:35:00.560
So that's one option.

00:35:00.560 --> 00:35:03.560
The other option here is, let me scroll down a little bit.

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:07.600
Okay, the other option,

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:09.399
which is the one that I'll focus on here for a moment,

00:35:09.399 --> 00:35:11.479
is deploying the model.

00:35:11.479 --> 00:35:13.280
SageMaker provides native tooling

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:14.260
for being able to take a model

00:35:14.260 --> 00:35:15.879
that's been trained in SageMaker

00:35:15.879 --> 00:35:20.879
and deploy it directly into SageMaker itself as an endpoint.

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:22.860
And then from that endpoint,

00:35:22.860 --> 00:35:25.000
you can now generate real-time predictions

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:27.959
by submitting either HTTP requests to the endpoint

00:35:27.959 --> 00:35:29.179
through other tools,

00:35:29.179 --> 00:35:31.959
like you might create a Shiny application

00:35:31.959 --> 00:35:33.639
that queries that endpoint

00:35:33.639 --> 00:35:36.439
and generates real-time requests based on user input.

00:35:36.439 --> 00:35:39.080
You might have a front-end mobile application

00:35:39.080 --> 00:35:40.280
that's built within your organization

00:35:40.280 --> 00:35:42.000
that queries this model

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:44.360
through this deployed endpoint that you create.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:47.840
Like I mentioned, SageMaker has native support

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:50.600
for deploying these endpoints for certain types of models.

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:52.919
This XGB model that we've trained here

00:35:52.919 --> 00:35:54.479
is one such example of those.

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:56.679
And so here we can see,

00:35:56.679 --> 00:35:58.959
we use this deploy method on our tuner object

00:35:58.959 --> 00:36:02.479
to deploy this model into this environment.

00:36:02.479 --> 00:36:04.040
And then once that model has been deployed,

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:05.760
we can define a serializer for it,

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:09.719
and we can use this predict method on the model itself

00:36:09.719 --> 00:36:12.919
to submit requests to that endpoint, generate predictions,

00:36:12.919 --> 00:36:14.120
and bring those predictions back

00:36:14.120 --> 00:36:16.679
into our existing R session.

00:36:16.679 --> 00:36:18.120
Now, let me come back up

00:36:18.120 --> 00:36:21.520
and just see if our tuning job has made any progress here.

00:36:22.959 --> 00:36:25.239
And we can take a look at where we're at.

00:36:27.919 --> 00:36:29.800
Okay, so we have four succeeded models.

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:30.639
We have four models

00:36:30.639 --> 00:36:32.479
that are currently in progress being trained.

00:36:32.479 --> 00:36:33.879
I'm not going to wait for that to conclude,

00:36:33.879 --> 00:36:35.360
but we see that we're making progress here,

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:37.679
and we can continue to query that progress

00:36:37.679 --> 00:36:39.199
using this Boto3 library

00:36:39.199 --> 00:36:41.360
that we've brought into our R session.

00:36:41.360 --> 00:36:43.360
Now, I'm going to come back into,

00:36:43.360 --> 00:36:46.040
let me see if I can get back into it here.

00:36:46.040 --> 00:36:47.840
Okay, so here I'm in SageMaker.

00:36:48.560 --> 00:36:50.360
This is the SageMaker studio,

00:36:50.360 --> 00:36:51.760
so the JupyterLab interface.

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:53.120
And the one other thing that I wanted to highlight

00:36:53.120 --> 00:36:55.560
is if I come down here, I can see this.

00:36:55.560 --> 00:36:57.360
I have the SageMaker resources view

00:36:57.360 --> 00:36:58.760
that's available to me here,

00:36:58.760 --> 00:37:01.280
and I can come in and I can look at this endpoint section,

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:04.040
and I can see these are previously deployed endpoints

00:37:04.040 --> 00:37:05.919
that I have published in preparation

00:37:05.919 --> 00:37:07.280
for our discussion today.

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:08.120
So here I can see,

00:37:08.120 --> 00:37:10.520
these are both models trained on the same data,

00:37:10.520 --> 00:37:12.360
just on separate days,

00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:14.239
but I can come in here and click on one of these,

00:37:14.239 --> 00:37:16.080
and I can open up an entire view

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:17.959
into what that model looks like.

00:37:17.959 --> 00:37:20.479
And here I can submit test requests to the model.

00:37:20.479 --> 00:37:23.679
I can view how this model is set up,

00:37:23.679 --> 00:37:25.479
what the endpoint for the model is,

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:28.439
information about the runtime of the model.

00:37:28.439 --> 00:37:32.159
If I had specified that I wanted to enable model tracking,

00:37:32.159 --> 00:37:36.040
I could view things like quality, explainability, bias.

00:37:36.040 --> 00:37:38.199
These types of metrics are supported in SageMaker

00:37:38.199 --> 00:37:40.080
as long as I configure my deployment

00:37:40.080 --> 00:37:42.919
to allow for tracking and metric collection,

00:37:42.919 --> 00:37:45.719
which I haven't done in this case,

00:37:45.959 --> 00:37:47.080
but it is something that's available

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:49.239
if that's something that's of interest.

00:37:49.239 --> 00:37:51.360
Now, to back up a little bit, right?

00:37:51.360 --> 00:37:53.080
If we come back here for a second,

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:56.840
what's the big deal?

00:37:56.840 --> 00:37:57.719
What's the excitement about this?

00:37:57.719 --> 00:37:59.639
Well, there's kind of two things.

00:37:59.639 --> 00:38:03.199
One is maybe the, depending on your perspective,

00:38:03.199 --> 00:38:07.760
might be the less exciting of the two things here,

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:10.560
but that is the fact that you can, as an RStudio customer,

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:13.360
you can bring existing RStudio Workbench licenses

00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:16.199
into SageMaker and use RStudio Workbench

00:38:16.199 --> 00:38:18.080
within your SageMaker environment.

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:20.919
Now you have an entirely managed hosted solution

00:38:20.919 --> 00:38:22.879
of RStudio Workbench that you don't need to worry

00:38:22.879 --> 00:38:25.040
about maintaining, installing, updating,

00:38:25.040 --> 00:38:27.639
or anything like that, but it remains flexible

00:38:27.639 --> 00:38:31.000
and gives you lots of resources at your disposal

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
for doing your day-to-day analysis

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.600
inside of a native RStudio environment.

00:38:36.679 --> 00:38:38.760
The other thing that we've just looked at

00:38:38.760 --> 00:38:41.179
is once you're in that environment as an R user,

00:38:41.179 --> 00:38:45.020
you gain access to a whole collection of SageMaker tools

00:38:45.020 --> 00:38:47.379
from model training and tuning to deployment,

00:38:47.379 --> 00:38:50.060
monitoring, all those things are now available to you

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:51.780
directly from within your SageMaker environment.

00:38:51.780 --> 00:38:55.379
Now, today, that access is managed through reticulate,

00:38:55.379 --> 00:38:57.620
like we walked through in the example just now.

00:38:57.620 --> 00:38:59.659
So using the reticulate package,

00:38:59.659 --> 00:39:02.060
we can bring in the SageMaker SDK,

00:39:02.060 --> 00:39:03.459
and then we can use that to interact

00:39:03.459 --> 00:39:04.659
with the SageMaker environment,

00:39:04.659 --> 00:39:06.979
from model training and tuning to deployment

00:39:06.979 --> 00:39:09.780
and any other things that we might want to interact with.

00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:14.939
Now, kind of as we look towards the future

00:39:14.939 --> 00:39:17.860
and what's coming up in this space,

00:39:17.860 --> 00:39:20.179
one of the kind of immediate term things to be addressed

00:39:20.179 --> 00:39:21.540
is that there will soon be the ability

00:39:21.540 --> 00:39:24.060
to bring custom images for RStudio Workbench

00:39:24.060 --> 00:39:26.020
in Amazon SageMaker.

00:39:26.020 --> 00:39:26.939
So if we come back here,

00:39:26.939 --> 00:39:29.540
just to remind us of what that looks like,

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:32.699
if we come back into our home screen here,

00:39:32.699 --> 00:39:34.260
when we start a new session,

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:38.020
currently there's only one image available to select from,

00:39:38.020 --> 00:39:39.540
but that will change in the near future,

00:39:39.780 --> 00:39:40.620
and there will be the ability

00:39:40.620 --> 00:39:44.260
to bring additional custom images into RStudio Workbench.

00:39:44.260 --> 00:39:46.260
You could define your own images within your organization.

00:39:46.260 --> 00:39:48.500
There may be predefined other images that are available

00:39:48.500 --> 00:39:50.260
that could contain different libraries,

00:39:50.260 --> 00:39:51.580
different versions of R

00:39:51.580 --> 00:39:55.020
that would support the use case that you're after.

00:39:55.020 --> 00:39:56.419
The other thing that we're really excited about

00:39:56.419 --> 00:39:57.979
and actually working on bringing to the table

00:39:57.979 --> 00:40:00.179
is RStudio Connect managed by SageMaker

00:40:00.179 --> 00:40:01.979
in the same way that we see RStudio Workbench

00:40:01.979 --> 00:40:03.620
managed by SageMaker today.

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:07.300
Now, it is possible today to use RStudio Connect

00:40:07.300 --> 00:40:11.060
and install it and manage within your own environment

00:40:11.060 --> 00:40:12.699
in connection with RStudio Workbench

00:40:12.699 --> 00:40:14.379
installed and managed by SageMaker.

00:40:14.379 --> 00:40:15.580
And what that process would look like

00:40:15.580 --> 00:40:17.179
is you would develop and do your work

00:40:17.179 --> 00:40:20.060
inside of RStudio Workbench in the SageMaker environment.

00:40:20.060 --> 00:40:21.300
And then when it came time to publish

00:40:21.300 --> 00:40:22.419
what you were working on,

00:40:22.419 --> 00:40:24.379
you would just publish that to Connect.

00:40:24.379 --> 00:40:26.340
And Connect might, in this case,

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:28.139
Connect would be something that you've installed

00:40:28.139 --> 00:40:29.699
and managed somewhere else.

00:40:29.699 --> 00:40:30.540
But down the road,

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:33.699
we anticipate bringing RStudio Connect to SageMaker as well

00:40:33.699 --> 00:40:34.540
in much in the same way

00:40:34.540 --> 00:40:37.100
that we have RStudio Workbench integrated there today.

00:40:37.780 --> 00:40:41.300
When you set up the RStudio integration on SageMaker,

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:42.899
one of the things that you have the ability to do

00:40:42.899 --> 00:40:47.459
is to predefine your both RStudio Connect URL

00:40:47.459 --> 00:40:49.100
if you already have an RStudio Connect environment

00:40:49.100 --> 00:40:52.379
and you want to automatically configure that

00:40:52.379 --> 00:40:53.540
for publishing from Workbench.

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:56.540
You can do that when you set up Workbench on SageMaker.

00:40:56.540 --> 00:40:58.699
And then the other thing is you can automatically define

00:40:58.699 --> 00:41:03.379
or you can set up and define an RStudio Package Manager URL

00:41:03.379 --> 00:41:06.379
for users to use when you go through the setup process.

