00:54:10.580 --> 00:54:13.139
Next question was an anonymous one that was,

00:54:13.139 --> 00:54:15.899
is RStudio Workbench fully on SageMaker

00:54:15.899 --> 00:54:19.139
or is it using SageMaker as a launcher backend,

00:54:19.139 --> 00:54:22.500
which would still require a front-end Workbench server?

00:54:22.500 --> 00:54:23.699
Oh man, such a good question.

00:54:23.699 --> 00:54:24.899
I meant to talk to this point

00:54:24.899 --> 00:54:26.500
because it's a very nuanced question,

00:54:26.500 --> 00:54:27.659
but it's a good one.

00:54:27.659 --> 00:54:30.500
So when you set up your SageMaker domain

00:54:30.500 --> 00:54:31.739
to support RStudio,

00:54:31.739 --> 00:54:32.699
one of the things that you do

00:54:32.699 --> 00:54:35.300
is you identify a persistent instance

00:54:35.300 --> 00:54:37.620
that will host RStudio.

00:54:38.139 --> 00:54:39.060
So you're right,

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:41.219
there does need to be some persistent environment

00:54:41.219 --> 00:54:43.659
that runs, that then launches these sessions

00:54:43.659 --> 00:54:46.620
into SageMaker and allow SageMaker

00:54:46.620 --> 00:54:48.659
to manage the resources behind those sessions.

00:54:48.659 --> 00:54:51.179
So there is that persistent environment.

00:54:51.179 --> 00:54:52.300
I believe the default,

00:54:52.300 --> 00:54:53.379
and it doesn't need to be very big

00:54:53.379 --> 00:54:55.419
because there's not any computation happening there.

00:54:55.419 --> 00:54:57.860
That environment gets automatically provisioned for you

00:54:57.860 --> 00:55:00.260
when you set up this inside your SageMaker domain

00:55:00.260 --> 00:55:02.780
and you can decide what instance type you want.

00:55:02.780 --> 00:55:03.620
I'm trying to remember,

00:55:03.620 --> 00:55:07.580
I think T3 medium is kind of the default.

00:55:08.419 --> 00:55:09.979
And I believe that SageMaker gives that to you for free,

00:55:09.979 --> 00:55:12.500
like as part of the RStudio offering on SageMaker,

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:14.060
that that host environment

00:55:14.060 --> 00:55:15.459
that's just running constantly

00:55:15.459 --> 00:55:18.699
to support the RStudio front end is there,

00:55:18.699 --> 00:55:20.780
but it's still maintained by SageMaker.

00:55:20.780 --> 00:55:24.340
And I don't believe it's something that's charged for.

00:55:24.340 --> 00:55:26.620
Yeah, just a quick comment on that, James,

00:55:26.620 --> 00:55:29.739
you're right, both on the instance type,

00:55:29.739 --> 00:55:32.139
it's T3 medium and it's also free.

00:55:33.060 --> 00:55:34.820
Perfect, thank you for confirming.

00:55:35.820 --> 00:55:39.780
Awesome, there's another question that was,

00:55:39.780 --> 00:55:43.020
what are the expectations for environment management?

00:55:43.020 --> 00:55:46.580
Is it managed by AWS, RStudio, me?

00:55:46.580 --> 00:55:48.419
Will I have access to the same environment

00:55:48.419 --> 00:55:51.219
two years from now to maintain reproducibility?

00:55:52.419 --> 00:55:56.659
Yeah, so I think there's two sides to this question

00:55:56.659 --> 00:55:58.580
because environment can mean a couple of things.

00:55:58.580 --> 00:56:01.620
So one is like your local R environment

00:56:01.620 --> 00:56:03.100
is within your control.

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:05.939
So if you want, you can install packages,

00:56:05.939 --> 00:56:07.219
those will go into your home directory,

00:56:07.219 --> 00:56:09.580
that home directory is persistent, like we mentioned.

00:56:09.580 --> 00:56:11.260
So different sessions that start

00:56:11.260 --> 00:56:13.179
will have the same access to the same files

00:56:13.179 --> 00:56:16.379
and packages that you were working with previously.

00:56:16.379 --> 00:56:18.860
And what that means is that there's support for things,

00:56:18.860 --> 00:56:20.340
there's automatically, because of that fact,

00:56:20.340 --> 00:56:21.860
there's automatically support for things like RM.

00:56:21.860 --> 00:56:24.659
So if you wanted to create a very specific collection

00:56:24.659 --> 00:56:26.340
of packages for a very specific project

00:56:26.340 --> 00:56:29.020
and have those version to a very specific set of versions,

00:56:29.020 --> 00:56:32.020
that's totally supported through tools like RM.

00:56:33.620 --> 00:56:36.540
In combination with what you're getting out of SageMaker.

00:56:36.540 --> 00:56:38.899
So your local environment, totally within your control,

00:56:38.899 --> 00:56:40.100
and certainly you can set it up

00:56:40.100 --> 00:56:41.939
so that you can come back to that environment

00:56:41.939 --> 00:56:42.780
two years down the road

00:56:42.780 --> 00:56:45.939
and reinstantiate it the way that it was

00:56:45.939 --> 00:56:48.699
and continue working from where you left off.

00:56:48.699 --> 00:56:50.020
The other side of this is,

00:56:50.020 --> 00:56:52.419
what about the administrative environment?

00:56:52.419 --> 00:56:56.219
The server, the settings for RStudio Workbench,

00:56:56.219 --> 00:56:57.060
things like that.

00:56:57.060 --> 00:56:59.739
That's something that falls under the SageMaker control,

00:56:59.739 --> 00:57:00.899
under SageMaker's control, right?

00:57:00.899 --> 00:57:02.979
So when you say, look, I'm gonna set up

00:57:03.860 --> 00:57:05.300
and manage RStudio Workbench through SageMaker,

00:57:05.300 --> 00:57:06.540
part of what you're doing is saying,

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:07.699
I'm gonna let SageMaker

00:57:07.699 --> 00:57:10.820
handle the RStudio administrative tasks for me,

00:57:10.820 --> 00:57:12.020
which can be a huge benefit

00:57:12.020 --> 00:57:13.939
because I don't have to worry about that stuff anymore.

00:57:13.939 --> 00:57:15.620
And in this particularly,

00:57:15.620 --> 00:57:17.939
I'm really excited to see how this helps.

00:57:17.939 --> 00:57:19.100
We work with a lot of organizations

00:57:19.100 --> 00:57:20.219
that are very Windows centric

00:57:20.219 --> 00:57:21.060
and all of our software

00:57:21.060 --> 00:57:22.540
needs to be installed in Linux environments.

00:57:22.540 --> 00:57:24.739
And that sometimes is a big hurdle to overcome.

00:57:24.739 --> 00:57:25.580
Now all of a sudden you can say, look,

00:57:25.580 --> 00:57:27.780
I'm just gonna let SageMaker manage and host it for me.

00:57:27.780 --> 00:57:29.340
And I don't need to worry about

00:57:29.340 --> 00:57:30.580
all the Linux stuff behind the scenes.

00:57:30.580 --> 00:57:32.139
As long as I can work with AWS

00:57:32.139 --> 00:57:34.060
to get the domain set up right,

00:57:34.060 --> 00:57:36.219
then I've got an environment I can use.

00:57:36.219 --> 00:57:37.939
But the other thing that that means is

00:57:37.939 --> 00:57:39.780
that I'm letting SageMaker handle that for me.

00:57:39.780 --> 00:57:41.100
So if there's questions or concerns

00:57:41.100 --> 00:57:42.419
or things that I want adjusted there,

00:57:42.419 --> 00:57:44.620
or features that I want enabled or whatever,

00:57:44.620 --> 00:57:47.179
that becomes a conversation to have with SageMaker.

00:57:49.179 --> 00:57:51.060
And then it looks like, sorry, just real quick.

00:57:51.060 --> 00:57:54.060
There was a clarification in the chat about,

