00:58:02.100 --> 00:58:03.179
well, two things.

00:58:03.179 --> 00:58:06.100
One is you have currently today,

00:58:06.100 --> 00:58:09.100
when you're in your session running on SageMaker,

00:58:09.100 --> 00:58:11.939
you have root access to that container.

00:58:11.939 --> 00:58:13.979
So when you go into the terminal tab of RStudio,

00:58:13.979 --> 00:58:16.100
you have already assumed the root role.

00:58:16.100 --> 00:58:17.899
So you can modify that container as you need.

00:58:17.899 --> 00:58:19.020
So if there's a system dependency

00:58:19.020 --> 00:58:20.060
that you're in the middle of a project

00:58:20.060 --> 00:58:22.020
and you're like, oh no, I needed this thing.

00:58:22.020 --> 00:58:23.860
You should be able to get in,

00:58:23.860 --> 00:58:25.459
add it to that container at that time

00:58:25.459 --> 00:58:27.419
and run with it from there.

00:58:27.419 --> 00:58:29.540
Now that's not persistent though, right?

00:58:29.540 --> 00:58:31.100
So if that session terminates

00:58:31.580 --> 00:58:32.860
and that container goes away and I start a new session,

00:58:32.860 --> 00:58:35.939
I'm gonna have to reinstall that dependency at that point.

00:58:35.939 --> 00:58:37.979
I can do it, but it's not persistent.

00:58:37.979 --> 00:58:40.540
The other side is this custom image functionality

00:58:40.540 --> 00:58:43.179
that we anticipate coming to SageMaker in the near future,

00:58:43.179 --> 00:58:46.139
which would allow you to identify at the Docker level

00:58:46.139 --> 00:58:48.419
as you build out these Docker files,

00:58:48.419 --> 00:58:49.979
what system dependencies you need available

00:58:49.979 --> 00:58:50.820
in your environment.

00:58:50.820 --> 00:58:53.260
And that's how you would manage those persistently.

